# 有了[[自由|自由]]才有辦法發展出責任心。

===管理===

薩德伯里學校的所有管理層面都是由每週的校務會議決定，這是源自[[新英格蘭|新英格蘭]]地區的[[鎮集會|鎮集會]]傳統<ref>{{cite news|title=Students revel in free-for-all|date=1992-04-19|work=Telegram & Gazette|location=Worcester, Massachusetts}}</ref>。校務會議決定學校的校規、分配預算、以及人員的聘用和開除。大部份的決策都是[[多數決|多數決]]，在場的每一個人，包括所有的學生和教職員，都有等值的一票。<ref name=Ellis/><ref>{{cite news|title=In Woodstock, a nonschool with nonteachers.(Hudson Valley Sudbury School, Woodstock, New York)|last=Rowe|first=Claudia|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2002-02-20}}</ref>

校規通常會整理成一本書，定期更新。通常違規或爭議都有一定的處理程序，包括調查、公聽會、審判、和判決，並允許上訴<ref>{{Cite web|last=Feldman|first=Jay|title=The Moral Behavior of Children and Adolescents at a Democratic School|series=Paper presented at 82nd American Educational Research Association Meeting|location=[[Seattle|Seattle]]|year=2001|url=http://eric.ed.gov/ERICDocs/data/ericdocs2sql/content_storage_01/0000019b/80/23/12/00.pdf}}</ref>。這是因為相信學生應該面對自己的行為造成的後果<ref>{{cite book|title=A Nation of Wimps: The High Cost of Invasive Parenting|last=Marano|first=Hara Estroff|year=2008|publisher=[[藍燈書屋|藍燈書屋]]|isbn=0-7679-2403-7|page=237}}</ref>。

===學習===
薩德伯里式的教育理論認為所有的人類行為都會自然而然地造成學習<ref name="Holzman">{{cite book|title= Schools for Growth: Radical Alternatives To Current Education Models|url= https://archive.org/details/schoolsforgrowth0000holz|last= Holzman|first= Lois|year= 1997|publisher=Lawrence Erlbaum Associates |location= United Kingdom|isbn= 0-8058-2357-3|pages= [https://archive.org/details/schoolsforgrowth0000holz/page/97 97]–99}}</ref>，學習是自發的、主動的  <ref>{{cite web|title=Self-governed, Sudbury Valley School begins in Massachusetts in History of Education: Selected Moments of the 20th Century|url=http://www.oise.utoronto.ca/research/edu20/moments/1968sudbury.html|first=Daniel|last=Schugurensky|work=Ontario Institute for Studies in Education, [[多倫多大學|多倫多大學]]|year=2003|accessdate=2009-08-31}}</ref>。學習是你自己做的事，不是別人施加在你身上的<ref>Greenberg, D. (1987) The Sudbury Valley School Experience [http://www.sudval.com/05_underlyingideas.html#09 ''Back to Basics''] {{Wayback|url=http://www.sudval.com/05_underlyingideas.html |date=20110511175026 }}. Retrieved, December 27, 2009.</ref>，因此老師的導引不是必要的。讓人們自由交換意見和想法，自由對話和互動，可以讓人廣泛地接觸到他覺得重要或有趣的主題。混合不同年齡的學生讓不同年齡的人可以互相學習，年長的學生可以成為年幼學生的正面或負面表率<ref name="Holzman"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/freedom-learn/200809/why-we-should-stop-segregating-children-age-part-i-the-value-play-in-the-z|title=Why We Should Stop Segregating Children by Age: Part I--The Value of Play in the Zone of Proximal Development |date=2008-09-09|accessdate=2009-10-25 |last=Gray |first=Peter |publisher=Psychology Today}}.</ref>。因為學習過程中有大量的玩樂，初次參觀的人常覺得學生無時無刻不在[[下課|下課]]時間<ref>Gee, James Paul (2003). [http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/11.05/view.html "Games, not school, are teaching kids to think,"] High Score Education, Wired Magazine. Retrieved 2010-7-10.</ref>。

薩德伯里學校的學生直接或間接地負責自己的教育，學生自己是唯一安排課程內容的人，除非學生自己要求上某一門課或是安排了[[師徒制|師徒制]]。薩德伯里學校不會比較學生的[[成績|成績]]，學校沒有[[考試|考試]]、評量或成績單。

舉例來說，閱讀識字的能力，每個學生都可以自由決定什麼時候要學。只有很少數的學生會特別找人幫忙，每個人都有自己的學習方式。有的人會聽別人唸故事，自己記住，然後漸漸學會自己閱讀；有的從食物包裝上面學會、有的讀遊戲的[[說明書|說明書]]、還有一些從路上的招牌學習。有些學生從字母發音開始學，有的練習[[音節|音節]]，有的一次學一整個字。老師們常常也不知道學生怎麼學會閱讀的，學生也很少告訴老師。薩德伯里山谷學校宣稱他們的學生全部都能學會閱讀。每個學生學會閱讀的年記都不一樣，而較晚學會閱讀也似乎沒有任何不良後果。<ref name="Greenberg1995">{{cite book|author=Daniel Greenberg|title=Free at Last: The Sudbury Valley School Press|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=es2nOuZE0rAC|accessdate=1 May 2013|date=1 June 1995|publisher=The Sudbury Valley School Press|isbn=978-1-888947-00-7}}, p34</ref><ref>John Taylor Gatto (2000-2003) The Underground History of American Education - A Schoolteacher's Intimate Investigation Into The Problem Of Modern Schooling, Chapter Three - Eyeless In Gaza, [http://johntaylorgatto.com/chapters/3d.htm ''The Sudbury Valley School''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102154119/http://www.johntaylorgatto.com/chapters/3d.htm |date=2010-01-02 }}. Retrieved, December 27, 2009.</ref>

==成效==
針對薩德伯里學校的研究有限，且不易將學生家庭背景的影響排除。但是針對「個人化學習」的研究顯示，自主學習環境下自定學習步調的學生，他們的數學和閱讀能力都顯著高於一般學校的學生，且弱勢學生的進步幅度大於一般學生；除此之外教師普遍對環境感到滿意。<ref>{{cite report|url=http://k12education.gatesfoundation.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Early-Progress-on-Personalized-Learning-Full-Report.pdf|type=pdf|title=Early Progress: Interim Research on Personalized Learning|authors=RAND Corporation|publisher=Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation|date=2014-11}}</ref>

